[Luke 12:28](../../../bib/kjv/luk012.htm#028.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_028">luk 12:28</span></span>

Which is to-day in the field

Construe in the field with the grass; and render is absolutely: exists,
lives. So Rev., the grass in the field which to-day is.

Oven (κλίβανον)

Strictly, a covered earthen vessel, wider at bottom than at top, in
which bread was baked by putting hot embers round it. The regular oven
or furnace is ἰπνός. Herodotus, speaking of the papyrus-plant (byblus),
the lower portion of which is used for food, says, "Such as wish to
enjoy the by-blue in full perfection, bake it first in a closed vessel
(ἐν κλιβάνῳ), heated to a glow" (ii., 92).

And seek not what ye, etc

Ye is emphatic: "and ye, seek not what," etc.

[Luke 12:29](../../../bib/kjv/luk012.htm#029.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_029">luk 12:29</span></span>

Be ye of doubtful mind (μετεωρίζεσθε)

Only here in New Testament. The verb primarily means to raise to a
height; buoy up, as with false hopes; and so to unsettle, or excite, or
keep in fluctuation. Thus Thucydides says of the war between Athens and
Sparta: "All Hellas was excited (μετέωρος) by the coming conflict
between the two chief cities" (ii., 8).

